Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The challenge of evaluating AI-generated explanations is not merely technical—it is deeply cognitive and contextual. Existing evaluation frameworks (e.g., IAEval) focus on structural or statistical properties like stability and plausibility, while others (e.g., InteractEva) emphasize system-level interaction but lack granular human judgment integration. Meanwhile, subjective assessments in XAI often treat users as homogeneous, ignoring individual differences in background, expertise, and cognitive preferences. My intuition is that explanation quality cannot be universally defined; instead, it must adapt to the *perceiver*. A doctor, a data scientist, and a layperson may judge the "intuitiveness" of an explanation differently—even when multiple technically valid explanations exist. Therefore, a novel framework should not only incorporate human judgments but also *model and personalize* them. Unlike prior work, this idea introduces dynamic adaptation: using online feedback to update user-specific intuitiveness models, enabling real-time calibration of explanation evaluation. This shifts the paradigm from static metrics to adaptive, user-aware assessment. The key innovation lies in combining psychometric modeling with machine learning to create personalized evaluation functions—something not addressed in current literature. Furthermore, by formalizing "explanation space ambiguity" (i.e., multiple valid rationales), the framework acknowledges epistemic pluralism in interpretability, making it more robust than binary correctness-based evaluations.

