Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: While the original PIAEE framework is highly innovative in its focus on personalized intuitiveness and adaptive evaluation, it relies heavily on real human feedback—both explicit and implicit—which limits scalability and increases deployment complexity. Drawing inspiration from Papers 1 and 3 (InteractEva), which advocate for simulation-based evaluation of interactive systems, I propose a transformative extension: replacing or augmenting actual user data with *cognitively grounded user simulators* that model diverse human reasoning styles. This leads to a new concept—**Simulated Intuitiveness Modeling (SIM-XAI)**—a scalable, simulation-driven framework that evaluates explanation quality by emulating a spectrum of human judgment patterns without requiring live participants during development. Unlike PIAEE, which personalizes post-hoc via data collection, SIM-XAI enables *prospective evaluation*, allowing developers to test how explanations perform across cognitive archetypes (e.g., novice vs. expert, analytical vs. heuristic thinkers) before deployment. By integrating cognitive science principles—such as dual-process theory and mental model alignment—into agent-based simulations, this approach not only preserves the core insight of subjectivity in intuitiveness but operationalizes it through generative behavioral modeling. Furthermore, while IAEval offers comprehensive dimensions for IA methods, it lacks human-centric interpretability metrics; SIM-XAI fills this gap by introducing "intuitiveness robustness" as a measurable property under varying simulated cognitive conditions. The novelty lies in decoupling subjective evaluation from direct human involvement, enabling faster, fairer, and more systematic XAI testing at scale.

